ele</i>, either of which might be a pet form of <i>Elias</i> or less commonly of <i>Niel</i> (from Latin <i>Nigellus</i>). See also   Neal  .","Americanized form of Swedish   Nilsson   and also of the Danish, Norwegian, and North German cognates   Nielsen   and   Nilsen   (compare   Nelsen  ). Compare also   Neilson   and   Nielson  .","History: The Nelson name was an important one in 18th-century VA, starting with Thomas ‘Scotch Tom’ Nelson, who emigrated to VA at the close of the 17th century from Penrith, Cumbria, where the Nelsons were numerous. Scotch Tom settled <i>c.</i> 1700 at Yorktown, VA, where he became a successful merchant and landholder. His son was sheriff and a member of the VA Council, and his grandson, Thomas Nelson (1738–89), a signer of the Declaration of Independence, was governor of VA."],"variants":[{"name":"Nell","meanings":["Dutch and German: from the personal name <i>Nel</i>, a shortened form of   Cornelius  .","South German: nickname from Middle High German <i>nelle</i> ‘crown of the head’, perhaps denoting an obstinate person.","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Nelle</i>. This may sometimes have been a variant of <i>Nele</i> (<i>Nigellus</i>, see   Neal  ), but it was probably more often a pet form of the commoner name <i>Elias</i> (see   Ellis  ) with a prosthetic <i>N-</i>."]}]},{"name":"Brenda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A very popular name, of uncertain derivation. Until the 20th century it was confined mainly to Scotland and Ireland. It is probably of Scandinavian rather than Celtic origin, however: a short form of any of the various compound names derived from Old Norse <i>brand</i> ‘sword’. Its popularity in Gaelic-speaking countries has no doubt been influenced by its similarity to   Brendan ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Kay","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the various names beginning with the letter <i>K-</i> (  compare  Dee   and   Jay  ), most notably   Katherine   and its many variants. It is also used independently. As a boy's name it may in part make reference to the name of the Arthurian knight Sir Kay, although he is not a particularly attractive character. His name is probably a Celticized form of Latin <i>Gaius</i>, an ancient Roman personal name of uncertain derivation. As a girl's name it was famous as that of the actress  Kay Kendall  (  1926–59 , original name  Justine McCarthy )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Brenda Kay Nelson was born about 1590, in England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Richard Toothaker, I."},"et":{"Est 1590–":"umbes 1590–Surnud","1586–1630":"1586–1630","1612–1638":"1612–1638","1590–Female":"1590–Surnud","1612":"1612","1630":"1630","1586":"1586","Est 1590":"umbes 1590","1590":"1590","1638":"1638",",, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England"},"fi":{"Est 1590–":"noin 1590–Kuollut","1586–1630":"1586–1630","1612–1638":"1612–1638","1590–Female":"1590–Kuollut","1612":"1612","1630":"1630","1586":"1586","Est 1590":"noin 1590","1590":"1590","1638":"1638",",, England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England"},"fr":{"Est 1590–":"environ 1590–Décédée","1586–1630":"1586–1630","1612–1638":"1612–1638","1590–Female":"1590–Décédée","1612":"1612","1630":"1630","1586":"1586","Est 1590":"environ 1590","1590":"1590","1638":"1638",",, England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","London, Middlesex, England":"Londres, Middlesex, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Brenda Kay Nelson est née environ 1590, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Richard Toothaker, I."},"de":{"Est 1590–":"um 1590–Verstorben","1586–1630":"1586–1630","1612–1638":"1612–1638","1590–Female":"1590–Verstorben","1612":"1612","1630":"1630","1586":"1586","Est 1590":"um 159